(216, 1, '2015-05-12 19:57:34', '2015-05-12 19:57:34', '<p class="p1">This is part 2 of Object Oriented Programming: Modeling blog series. You can read part 1 <a href="http://avenuecode.com/object-oriented-programming-modelling-part-1/" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p class="p1"><strong>Modeling our problem!</strong></p>\r\nNow let’s try to model this using JAVA.  Eventually, we’re going to use code to construct the cube from scratch, but for now, we’re thinking through <em>how </em>we’re going to go about doing that.  What kind of things will we need to build a cube?  (Keep in mind that there are multiple ways to accomplish the same thing, and this is just one way, chosen for simplicity.)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe’ll start with the most basic building blocks: the colors themselves.  There are 6 colors that we need for the Rubik’s cube.  Also, these colors are all fixed, so we will use an <strong>ENUM </strong>to accomplish this:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.46.24-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-493 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.46.24-PM-300x57.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.46.24 PM" width="300" height="57" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhat else do we have on a cube?  Pieces!  As we saw earlier, centers, edges and corners will be different based on how many colors each one has, but all of them do have some distinct set of colors and some distinct position on the cube.  So let’s think of all the possible positions we can have.  We can also create an ENUM for it.  (We use ENUM, rather than just using the numbers, mainly to make the code easier to read.  Anytime you have a FIXED number of elements that have only one property (like colors, or positions), your best but is to create an ENUM for it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe java will look something like this:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.47.40-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-494" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.47.40-PM-1024x324.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.47.40 PM" width="600" height="190" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo far, we’ve defined colors and positions.\r\n\r\nNow let’s apply these two things--A position and a color/set of colors-- to define our Pieces.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.48.29-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-495" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.48.29-PM-300x119.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.48.29 PM" width="300" height="119" /></a>\r\n\r\nNow let’s make finer distinctions for our 3 types of pieces -- Edges, Corners and Centers.  Although these are different, these are all still pieces, needing a position and a color/set of colors.  So we can use inheritance, a nifty tool of OOP so that these 3 new classes will each be defined like our ‘Piece’ class.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-496" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.49.13-PM-300x79.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.49.13 PM" width="300" height="79" />\r\n\r\nNow let’s define our last class: The cube itself.\r\n\r\nAs we talked about before, a cube is a set of 26 pieces and some methods to modify it.  We will also need a way to check if the cube is solved -- which will involved using a boolean which will check if the cube is solved and then return either “true” or “false.”\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-497" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.50.50-PM-1024x515.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.50.50 PM" width="600" height="302" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Instantiating our objects</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOk, now we modelled our problem in an abstract sense, but now we need a “real cube.”\r\n\r\nWe refer to the process of creating CONCRETE objects as <strong>INSTANTIATION.  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo instantiate a cube, we’ll need to start by instantiating its individual building blocks.  We need to instantiate each of its 26 distinct pieces.  Instantiating each piece involves 2 pieces of information, as we discussed earlier -- its position and its set of colors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo, using the class structure that we defined earlier, let’s instantiate a cube:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.52.31-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-498" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.52.31-PM-1024x116.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.52.31 PM" width="600" height="68" /></a>\r\n\r\nBut wait!  We modelled the position as a piece property, but we did more than we need to.  After all we don’t need to know where the piece will be placed on the cube in order to create it, right?  We can instead create a pile of individual pieces that we can put assemble later.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.57.36-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-499" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.57.36-PM-268x300.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.57.36 PM" width="268" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nSo let’s do a little change in our model:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.58.28-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-500" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.58.28-PM-300x180.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.58.28 PM" width="300" height="180" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMakes more sense, right?\r\n\r\nNotice that to do this we created a map.  A map associates is something we use to associate keys with values.  In this case, we are using the map to identify each piece with a particular spot on the cube.  Maps cannot contain duplicate keys, which is perfect for us since we cannot have more than one piece in each position in our cube.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo let’s try instantiating our cube again:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.11-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-501" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.11-PM-1024x310.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.59.11 PM" width="600" height="182" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAfter this, we will have something that looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.52-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-502" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.52-PM-288x300.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.59.52 PM" width="288" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow let’s add our edge pieces.\r\n\r\nFirst we instantiate the blue and yellow edge that will be our top front edge:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.00.48-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-503" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.00.48-PM-1024x82.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.00.48 PM" width="400" height="32" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.01.52-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-504" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.01.52-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.01.52 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNext, we place oru edge on the cube:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.15.57-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-506" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.15.57-PM-1024x75.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.15.57 PM" width="600" height="44" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHowever, we realize now that we are missing some crucial information: We don’t know which direction the piece is oriented.  It’s possible to place the cube so that it’s yellow side up, the correct way, but it can also be placed Blue up, incorrectly, as you can see:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.17.07-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-508" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.17.07-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.17.07 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a> <a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.16.53-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-507" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.16.53-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.16.53 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo what can we do?  We didn’t account for this in our original plan… But we can fix the problem on the go.  Let’s add an Orientation property to our piece:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.18.01-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-509 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.18.01-PM-300x112.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.18.01 PM" width="300" height="112" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow we have all the information necessary to create a cube.  It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.19-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-510" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.19-PM-1024x194.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.19.19 PM" width="600" height="114" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.36-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-511" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.36-PM-1024x726.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.19.36 PM" width="600" height="426" /></a>\r\n\r\nCongratulations!  We’ve completed the first step: Creating an elegantly modeled cube!  Our next step will be to design the methods and functions so that we can modify the initial state of our cube.  We’ll tackle this in a future post, in which, among other things, I will unveil to you the entrancing beauty of TDD… But more on this later.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Object Oriented Programming: Modeling (part 2)', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '210-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:57:34', '2015-05-12 19:57:34', '', 210, 'http://localhost/acnew/210-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
