(234, 1, '2014-07-16 21:38:30', '2014-07-16 21:38:30', 'Process and software implementation methods have been improving around the world very fast over the past years.\r\nNot so long ago, one of the first known software development processes, which is still being used by lonely programmers or unorganized companies, is the empiric “Code and Fix” process that is nothing else than a process based on a trial  and error or an absence of process. Building software in this way, in some cases, ended up making the developer a true hero.\r\nA more civilized way to construct software emerged in the Waterfall process model, when it was realized that software construction is something that can be made step by step.  If well managed, allows more complex software to be constructed to accomplish specific goals never thought before.\r\nWith the Waterfall model, phases were defined to split and organize in a sequential order in the software life cycle. Every phase is accomplished sequentially where the next phase starts only when the current one ends.\r\nBig projects from huge companies emerged, but most failed. Why? The theory behind Waterfall process is pretty wonderful, but cost and time started to be a huge hurdle for this model and some of those projects that succeeded by being finished, were failing later because it was not attending to customer’s needs anymore.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Waterfall_model_%281%29.svg/350px-Waterfall_model_%281%29.svg.png" alt="" width="350" height="263" />\r\n\r\nAfter years using Waterfall model which compiled many failed projects, unsatisfied customers, and millions of dollars spent, many attempts raised to try to solve and revert bad image caused by the Waterfall model. As a good attempt, we can talk about the Iterative and Incremental model.\r\nWith the Iterative and Incremental model, the idea to divide and conquer emerged for large systems. One or more small pieces are produced to work and be used to increment the system at end of iteration.\r\nEvery iteration happens similar to waterfall model, but in this case to build a small piece of working software to be integrated with the whole. When the system is finished, if a small piece was to fail, the whole system might still work because every piece was created independently.\r\n\r\nAnother evolutionary approach is the Spiral model.  This combines aspects of iterative and waterfall models besides of a special emphasis in analysis and risk management. Every cycle of this model iterates through four quadrants as the project is incrementally developed: define objectives, alternatives and constraints; analyze risks; develop product; plan next cycle.\r\nThe spiral model wasn’t still a very good process model to be used widely around the world, because its costs was too high to be applied and is not a good option for small projects.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone" src="http://www.designingprojectmanagement.com/images/Spiral%20process%20a%20software%20designing%20model.jpg" alt="" width="506" height="333" />\r\n\r\nGoing forward with more maturity and advanced practices, an evolved iterative and incremental process called RUP (Rational Unified Process), came up. Being Use Case and requirements driven, RUP which is based on the UP (Unified Process) model, utilizes Use Case to describe any interaction between the software system and anything external such as a user of the system. Use Cases are also very good to capture requirements in a way to provide a bird’s-eye view of the whole system, actors, external systems and interactions between.\r\n\r\nAnother good aspect of RUP is about the architecture whose try to describe static, dynamic, functional and non functional requirements of the overall system.\r\nWorking based on RUP theory seems to be wonderful on project’s world, with everything “well specified, well planned, well designed, and well tested.” The real world is pretty different. Mixed techniques started to be use. Engineers were trying to develop software using only the main parts of prior described process. Around the world they were trying to evolve software life cycle in a way to try to reduce costs and deliver  functional software faster.\r\nInitiatives like XP (eXtreme Programming) appeared and were well adopted by many companies and individual developers, to try to focus more on the code to create a final product. Agile movement were creating form. Other initiatives appeared to try to create architecture documentation, project management, tests and so on in a more agile way.\r\nAnother good example are the (Test Driven Development) TDD and more recently, (Acceptance Test Driven Development) ATDD, to try to produce code with automation tests to simplify integration process and bring agility. On TDD and ATDD the focus is to create the test cases, unity tests and integration tests before start codify client’s requirements.\r\nThe main idea of Agile is to drive software life cycle and delivery a functional product sooner. Agile does not try to eliminate documentation or methodology, but integrate team mates to communicate, follow and produce only what is crucial for some software project, creating the necessary documentation and doing all necessary steps to accomplish that project faster and with high quality.\r\n\r\nBy: Alexandre Menezes de Queiroz', 'Development of Software Implementation Methods', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'development-of-software-implementation-methods', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:18:32', '2015-05-18 17:18:32', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=234', 0, 'post', '', 0),
